.TH "WINDOW.GETCOMPUTEDSTYLE" "3JS" "December 17, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Window.getComputedStyle \- Window: getComputedStyle() method
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]Window.getComputedStyle()\f[B]\f[R] method returns a live
read\-only \f[CR]CSSStyleProperties\f[R] object containing the resolved
values of all CSS properties of an element, after applying active
stylesheets and resolving any computation those values may contain.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
getComputedStyle(element)
getComputedStyle(element, pseudoElt)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]element\f[R]
The \f[CR]Element\f[R] for which to get the computed style.
.TP
\f[B]pseudoElt\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string specifying the pseudo\-element to match.
Omitted (or \f[CR]null\f[R]) for real elements.
.SS Return value
A \f[I]live\f[R] \f[CR]CSSStyleProperties\f[R] object, which updates
automatically when the element\(cqs styles are changed.
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Earlier versions of the specification returned a
\f[CR]CSSStyleDeclaration\f[R] (from which \f[CR]CSSStyleProperties\f[R]
is derived).
See the browser compatibility table for browser support information.
.RE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Warning:\f[R] Returned values are sometimes deliberately
inaccurate.
To avoid the \(lqCSS History Leak\(rq security issue, browsers may lie
about the computed styles for a visited link, returning values as if the
user never visited the linked URL.
See \c
.UR https://blog.mozilla.org/security/2010/03/31/plugging-the-css-history-leak/
Plugging the CSS history leak
.UE \c
\ and \c
.UR https://hacks.mozilla.org/2010/03/privacy-related-changes-coming-to-css-vistited/
Privacy\-related changes coming to CSS \f[CR]:visited\f[R]
.UE \c
\ for examples of how this is implemented.
.RE
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
If the passed object is not an \f[CR]Element\f[R] or the
\f[CR]pseudoElt\f[R] is not a valid pseudo\-element selector or is
\f[CR]::part()\f[R] or \f[CR]::slotted()\f[R].
.RS
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] Valid pseudo\-element selector refers to syntactic
validity, e.g., \f[CR]::unsupported\f[R] is considered valid, even
though the pseudo\-element itself is not supported.
.RE
.RE
.SH DESCRIPTION
The method returns a live read\-only \f[CR]CSSStyleProperties\f[R]
object containing the resolved values of all CSS properties of an
element, after applying active stylesheets and resolving any computation
those values may contain.
.PP
The returned object can be used to inspect the element\(cqs styles \(em
including those set inline, using a \f[CR]<style>\f[R] element, or via
an external stylesheet.
Since the object read\-only you can\(cqt use it to set the styles of an
element.
However because it is \(lqlive\(rq, if you update the element styles
using another API (such as \f[CR]HTMLElement.style\f[R]), the returned
object will be updated with the corresponding resolved value.
.PP
The distinction that the object contains resolved values is important.
For most properties, in particular those that depend on layout such as
\f[CR]display\f[R], \f[CR]font\-size\f[R], or \f[CR]line\-height\f[R],
the resolved value is the computed value.
For properties that depend on layout, the used value may differ slightly
from the computed value, and this is what is returned as the resolved
value.
For an animating property value, it will be the computed value at the
current point in the animation.
.PP
The returned object has dash\-named and corresponding camel\-case named
properties for \f[B]all\f[R] CSS properties supported by the browser,
including both shorthand and longhand properties.
.PP
Shorthand CSS properties of the element are expanded to their
corresponding long\-form properties.
For example, an element with style
\f[CR]\(dqborder\-top: 1px solid black\(dq\f[R] would be represented in
the returned object by properties with the names \f[CR]border\-top\f[R]
and \f[CR]borderTop\f[R], and the corresponding longhand properties
\f[CR]border\-top\-color\f[R] and \f[CR]borderTopColor\f[R],
\f[CR]border\-top\-style\f[R] and \f[CR]borderTopStyle\f[R], and
\f[CR]border\-top\-width\f[R] and \f[CR]borderTopWidth\f[R].
.PP
Note that the returned object is the same type as the object returned
from the element\(cqs \f[CR]style\f[R] property.
However the \f[CR]element.style\f[R] object can also be used to
\f[B]set\f[R] styles on that element, and returns just the inline styles
or those set via JavaScript.
.SS Color values
For compatibility reasons, serialized color values specified using the
traditional sRGB color space are expressed as \f[CR]rgb()\f[R] colors if
the alpha channel value is exactly \f[CR]1\f[R], and \f[CR]rgba()\f[R]
colors otherwise.
The legacy syntax with commas is used, with commas as separators (for
example \f[CR]rgb(255, 0, 0)\f[R]).
.PP
For other color spaces the values are serialized using the corresponding
functional expressions: \f[CR]lab()\f[R], \f[CR]lch()\f[R]
\f[CR]oklab()\f[R], \f[CR]oklch()\f[R], \f[CR]color()\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Retrieving resolved styles
In this example we style a \f[CR]<p>\f[R] element, then retrieve those
styles using \f[CR]getComputedStyle()\f[R], and print them into the text
content of the \f[CR]<p>\f[R].
.SS HTML
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]p\f[R]>Hello</\f[B]p\f[R]>
.EE
.SS CSS
.IP
.EX
p {
  \f[B]width\f[R]: 400px;
  \f[B]margin\f[R]: 0 auto;
  \f[B]padding\f[R]: 20px;
  \f[B]font\f[R]: 2rem/2 sans\-serif;
  \f[B]text\-align\f[R]: center;
  \f[B]background\f[R]: purple;
  \f[B]color\f[R]: white;
}
.EE
.SS JavaScript
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] para = document.querySelector(\(dqp\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] compStyles = window.getComputedStyle(para);
para.textContent =
  \(gaMy computed font\-size is ${compStyles.getPropertyValue(\(dqfont\-size\(dq)},\(rsn\(ga +
  \(gaand my computed line\-height is ${compStyles.getPropertyValue(
    \(dqline\-height\(dq,
  )}.\(ga;
.EE
.SS Result
.SS Use with pseudo\-elements
\f[CR]getComputedStyle()\f[R] can pull style info from pseudo\-elements,
such as \f[CR]::after\f[R], \f[CR]::before\f[R], \f[CR]::marker\f[R], or
\f[CR]::line\-marker\f[R].
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]h3\f[R]>Generated content</\f[B]h3\f[R]>
.EE
.IP
.EX
h3\f[BI]::after\f[R] {
  \f[B]content\f[R]: \(dq rocks!\(dq;
}
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] h3 = document.querySelector(\(dqh3\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] result = getComputedStyle(h3, \(dq::after\(dq).content;

console.log(\(dqthe generated content is: \(dq, result); \f[I]// returns \(aq rocks!\(aq\f[R]
.EE
